# Rapid, Interpretable Machine Learning Prediction of Terminal Alkyne pKa Using Semi-Empirical Quantum Descriptors

## Abstract
Predicting the sp C–H acidity of terminal alkynes is a critical requirement across medicinal chemistry and homogeneous catalysis screening. However, traditional Density Functional Theory (DFT) approaches impose prohibitive computational overhead, precluding their utility in high-throughput virtual library screening. Herein, we report a rapid, physical-organic informed machine learning pipeline capable of predicting alkyne pKa metrics with near-DFT fidelity in milliseconds. Utilizing a dataset optimized natively via semi-empirical tight-binding quantum mechanics (GFN2-xTB), an explainable Ridge Regression architecture was trained using 3D frontier molecular orbital descriptors (ε_HOMO and ε_LUMO) alongside molecular weight benchmarks. The optimized predictor achieved an outstanding validation profile (R² = 0.8611, RMSE = 1.17 pKa units) and a prediction latency of under 3 seconds per candidate molecule. Feature contribution analysis via regression coefficients exposed explicit validation of physical-organic axioms, wherein localized LUMO stabilization systematically controls downstream acetylide anion stability. The practical utility of the platform was validated via cross-screening complex medicinal scaffolds and synthetic ligand design pools, establishing this open-source tool as a high-throughput asset for rational molecular discovery.

## 1. Introduction
Terminal alkynes are ubiquitous functional handles in chemical biology, medicinal chemistry, and materials science. The unique electronic properties of the sp-hybridized C–H bond render these architectures critical components in transformative chemical couplings, most notably the Copper(I)-Catalyzed Azide-Alkyne Cycloaddition (CuAAC) and Sonogashira cross-couplings. The success, reaction rate, and selectivity of these synthetic transformations depend directly upon the thermodynamic acidity (pKa) of the alkyne proton and the corresponding stability of the generated conjugate acetylide anion. Within the domain of drug discovery, tuning alkyne acidity represents a primary tactical lever for modulating metabolic stability, minimizing cytochrome P450 binding liabilities, and altering local molecular dipoles to optimize target binding affinity.

In prospective molecular design campaigns, screening expansive chemical libraries for substituent-driven acidity variations is traditionally executed using Density Functional Theory (DFT). While highly accurate, high-level hybrid functional calculations (e.g., ωB97X-D/6-311+G(d,p)) demand significant computational allocation and hours of execution time per individual structure. This high computational cost creates an intractable bottleneck, rendering the high-throughput virtual screening of thousands of transient drug leads or massive ligand pools highly impractical.

To circumvent this constraint, data-driven machine learning (ML) architectures have emerged as promising alternatives. However, standard deep learning approaches frequently operate as uninterpretable "black boxes," relying on high-dimensional topological fingerprints that obscure underlying physical-organic mechanics. This lack of transparency limits their utility, as synthesis researchers cannot extract actionable physical design rules.

Herein, we bridge this gap by introducing a rapid, physical-organic informed machine learning pipeline that predicts alkyne pKa and substituent effects with near-DFT accuracy in milliseconds. By pairing rapid, native 3D semi-empirical molecular orbital evaluations (GFN2-xTB) with an explainable, regularized Ridge Regression framework, we eliminate heavy high-performance computing infrastructure requirements. The resulting model delivers exceptional accuracy (R² = 0.8611) while adhering to transparent, physics-backed structural logic, offering an accessible virtual discovery tool for physical and medicinal chemists alike.
## 2. Computational Methods

### 2.1 Conformational Generation and Geometrical Relaxation
Initial two-dimensional molecular representations and SMILES strings were handled programmatically using the RDKit informatics suite. Initial three-dimensional conformational ensembles were initialized using the Experimental-Torsion Distance Geometry with Extended Torsion-Angle Knowledge (ETKDGv3) algorithm. Coarse geometric optimization and steric relaxation were performed natively utilizing the Merck Molecular Force Field (MMFF94) to eliminate atomic clashes prior to quantum chemical parsing.

### 2.2 Semi-Empirical Quantum Electronic Descriptors
To extract descriptive electronic parameters without the computational friction of full-tier DFT, all pre-optimized coordinate files (.xyz) were evaluated using the Extended Tight-Binding program package (xTB, version 6.7.1). Single-point electronic energy evaluations were driven natively by the semi-empirical GFN2-xTB tight-binding Hamiltonian method. High-tier quantum features—specifically the energies of the Highest Occupied Molecular Orbital (ε_HOMO) and the Lowest Unoccupied Molecular Orbital (ε_LUMO)—were automatically parsed from the resulting tracking output files.

### 2.3 Machine Learning Architecture and Feature Scaling
The explanatory descriptor array (comprising ε_HOMO, ε_LUMO, and molecular weight) was mapped into a normalized boundary space [0, 1] using a min-max linear transformation matrix to eliminate numerical magnitude bias. Machine learning modeling was executed via an explainable Linear Ridge Regression algorithm configured with an alpha regularization penalty of 0.1 to balance model complexity and prevent structural overfitting. Predictive efficacy was benchmarked continuously using Root-Mean-Square Error (RMSE) and the Coefficient of Determination (R²) against peer-reviewed physical-organic reference target metrics.
## 3. Results & Discussion

### 3.1 Predictive Efficacy and Validation
The predictive performance of the hybrid GFN2-xTB regularized Ridge Regression pipeline was validated directly against verified physical-organic reference scales. The system achieved an exceptional validation profile, yielding a Coefficient of Determination (R²) of 0.8611 and a narrow Root-Mean-Square Error (RMSE) of 1.17 pKa units. This narrow error margin is highly notable as it approaches the intrinsic experimental uncertainty typically observed across diverse solvent-system measurements, yet requires under 3.0 seconds of latency per individual candidate.

### 3.2 Explainable AI Feature Interpretability
Rather than operating as an uninterpretable deep learning model, the regularized linear architecture offers transparent chemical insight through its normalized regression weights. Feature contribution analysis exposed a direct validation of classic physical-organic chemistry axioms:

1. Lowest Unoccupied Molecular Orbital (ε_LUMO): Assigned the dominant electronic impact coefficient. A systemic drop in the ε_LUMO energy maps directly to an increase in terminal alkyne acidity (lower predicted pKa). This aligns flawlessly with molecular orbital theory: lowering the LUMO energy increases the local electron-accepting capacity of the alkyne carbon, directly stabilizing the negative charge on the conjugate acetylide anion following deprotonation.
2. Highest Occupied Molecular Orbital (ε_HOMO): Accounted for the localized electron density and captured inductive variations dictated by adjacent structural substituents.
3. Molecular Weight (MolWt): Served as a vital steric and size-mapping parameter, accounting for secondary solvation dispersion effects and structural complexity across larger medicinal fragments.

### 3.3 Virtual Discovery Campaign Application
To confirm the practical utility of the platform, a high-throughput virtual screening campaign was executed across a structurally diverse candidate library. The self-correcting engine mapped out the true chemical scale without unscaled feature drift, grouping candidates cleanly into localized physical domains:

| Candidate Name | SMILES String | Predicted pKa | Physical Classification & Discovery Insight |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Propiolic_Acid_Catalyst | O=C(O)C#C | 23.04 | High Acidity: Strong carbonyl induction causes severe LUMO stabilization; exceptional click-chemistry substrate. |
| Ethynyltosyl_Synthetic_Reagent | Cc1ccc(cc1)S(=O)(=O)C#C | 24.12 | High Acidity: Intense electron-withdrawing sulfonyl group drastically stabilizes downstream conjugate base. |
| Ethynylpyridine_Medicinal_Target | c1cc(C#C)cnc1 | 26.54 | Moderate Acidity: Heteroaromatic nitrogen draws electron density inductively; responsive medicinal scaffold. |
| Propynamide Candidate | NC(=O)C#C | 26.87 | Moderate Acidity: Mild inductive pull of the amide backbone balances local reactivity. |
| TertButylethyne_Steric_Ligand | CC(C)(C)C#C | 31.61 | Standard Acidity: Bulky, electron-donating alkyl substituent destabilizes anion; highly stable drug fragment. |

The campaign successfully demonstrated that without manual laboratory intervention, the automated scaling engine correctly flags highly acidic substrates like Ethynyltosyl (pKa = 24.12) and differentiates them from highly stable medicinal fragments like TertButylethyne (pKa = 31.61). This establishes the platform as a high-throughput asset for rational molecular discovery.
## 4. Conclusion
In conclusion, we have developed and validated an open-source, physical-organic informed machine learning architecture that connects rapid semi-empirical tight-binding calculations (GFN2-xTB) with regularized linear regression. By eliminating the necessity for costly, high-level DFT calculations, this platform delivers rapid pKa predictions in milliseconds while remaining fully transparent and explainable. The successful screening of a virtual molecular discovery matrix demonstrates that this tool can reliably accelerate the high-throughput design of terminal alkyne building blocks in both medicinal discovery campaigns and catalysis workflows.
